Japanese upstarts, huh?

40:54.861 --> 40:57.262
I don't think I'd fit in one.

40:57.330 --> 40:59.031
Oh, yeah, I hear you on that.

41:06.172 --> 41:08.773
Oh, great. Thanks.

41:08.841 --> 41:10.242
You bet.

41:12.345 --> 41:14.513
Well, I got to get back.

41:14.581 --> 41:17.617
Of course. After you.

41:20.020 --> 41:21.120
What's it called?

41:21.188 --> 41:22.856
A piroshki.

41:22.923 --> 41:25.125
It's like a meat dumpling.
They kind of like them.

41:25.193 --> 41:26.626
I kind of like them, too.
They're juicy. They're doughy.

41:26.694 --> 41:29.129
Amador: Mr. Beeman.

41:29.197 --> 41:30.964
This is Agent Gaad,
my former deputy.

41:31.032 --> 41:32.466
How you doing?

41:32.533 --> 41:33.800
He's detailed

41:33.868 --> 41:35.536
to a CIA Counterintelligence
task force

41:35.603 --> 41:37.371
at Langley.

41:37.439 --> 41:39.106
He's going to bring them
up to speed on Timoshev,

41:39.173 --> 41:41.775
and hopefully
they can help us out.

41:41.843 --> 41:42.809
Hi, Chris.

41:42.876 --> 41:44.377
Frank.

41:44.445 --> 41:46.179
Agent Beeman, do you think
there's any chance

41:46.246 --> 41:47.546
that Timoshev is still alive?

41:47.614 --> 41:49.448
Uh, he's been here
about 10 minutes, Frank.

41:49.516 --> 41:52.051
Well, it's my understanding
he has some special insight.

41:52.119 --> 41:54.253
Yeah,
my bank-robbery assignment,

41:54.321 --> 41:56.321
the last three years,
I was undercover.

41:56.389 --> 41:58.357
Undercover? With who?

41:58.425 --> 42:00.325
A white-supremacist group
out of Southern Arkansas.

42:00.393 --> 42:02.961
24 principals
currently awaiting trial.

42:03.029 --> 42:05.131
No shit. You were living it,
the whole nine yards?

42:05.198 --> 42:07.600
Yeah. I barely saw my family.

42:07.668 --> 42:09.936
That's one thing
we haven't had around here...

42:10.004 --> 42:11.371
someone with that mind-set.

42:11.439 --> 42:13.374
I thought you were here
for your good looks.

42:13.441 --> 42:15.142
On Timoshev, sir...

42:15.210 --> 42:17.311
when you're betrayed
by one of your own...

42:17.379 --> 42:19.647
Psst. Hey.

42:24.053 --> 42:25.754
When you're betrayed
by one of your own,

42:25.821 --> 42:27.889
you're not inclined to put him
out of his misery fast.

42:27.957 --> 42:29.791
I would bet the Russians
would go to considerable lengths

42:29.859 --> 42:31.126
to get him back there

42:31.193 --> 42:32.560
so they can look him in the eye

42:32.628 --> 42:34.395
before they blow
his brains out.

42:35.664 --> 42:37.398
If you grabbed him
but you couldn't get him

42:37.466 --> 42:38.799
out of the country right away,
where would you keep him?

42:38.867 --> 42:40.635
Well, I wouldn't take him
to the embassy.

42:40.702 --> 42:42.470
I wouldn't want to get near
any Russians,

42:42.538 --> 42:45.140
where we might be looking.

42:45.207 --> 42:47.909
Um, I wouldn't want to be
on the street,

42:47.976 --> 42:49.410
as much as I could avoid it,

42:49.478 --> 42:51.079
or anywhere
I didn't usually go.

42:51.147 --> 42:52.781
I would probably make a beeline

42:52.848 --> 42:54.983
to my house,
to tell you the truth.

42:55.051 --> 42:57.686
It's really the safest place you
can be, strange as that may sound.

42:57.754 --> 43:00.422
And I would just follow
my regular routine,

43:00.490 --> 43:02.958
keep him there
till the heat died down.

43:03.026 --> 43:05.093
Well, if he's at somebody's house,
we're never gonna find him.

43:05.161 --> 43:07.863
No, I wouldn't think so, sir.

43:07.931 --> 43:10.232
Well, thanks.

43:14.370 --> 43:15.671
So, were you, like,

43:15.738 --> 43:17.606
